NYC Storms & 311 Flooding Service Requests Part 2: Storm Identification & Spatial Queries#

part 1

part 2

part 3

The goal of this project is to:

(A) Use the local environmental record to identify storms in NYC from 2010-present

(B) Use flooding service requests made to 311 to identify storms in NYC from 2010-present

(C) Use the spatial distribution of flooding service requests made to 311 for each identified storm as proxy for flooding susceptibility due to storms.

This section covers

  1. Assembling a table of “likely storm events”.

  2. Using 311 complaints for each storm to identify areas susceptible to flooding.

from sqlalchemy import create_engine
import folium
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
import json

engine_str = "postgresql+psycopg2://docker:docker@0.0.0.0:25432/storms"
engine = create_engine(engine_str)

%load_ext sql
%sql $engine.url

'Connected: docker@storms'

QUEENS = [40.7292, -73.9049]

def rs_to_gdf(rs, geom_col='geom', epsg=4326):
    """sql result set to geodataframe"""
    df = rs.DataFrame()
    gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(df, geometry=gpd.GeoSeries.from_wkb(df[geom_col], crs=epsg))

    if epsg != 4326:
        gdf.to_crs(4326, inplace=True)
    return gdf

def to_map(result_set, location=QUEENS, geom_col='geom', epsg=4326, zoom=13, fillcolor='orange'):
    m = folium.Map(location=location, zoom_start=zoom)
    gdf = rs_to_gdf(result_set, geom_col=geom_col, epsg=epsg)

    geojson = json.loads(gdf.to_json())

    for r in geojson['features']:

        if 'properties' in r.keys():
            properties = r['properties']
        else:
            properties = None

        popup = folium.GeoJsonPopup([c for c in properties.keys() if geom_col not in c.lower()]) if properties is not None else None
        geo_j = folium.GeoJson(data=r,
                                style_function=lambda x: {'fillColor': fillcolor},
                                popup=popup
        )
        geo_j.add_to(m)

    return m

Summary of all Storm Events#

For each day in the study record, we have values for:

  • Water level (ft) at Battery Park

  • River Discharge (cubic ft/s) on Bronx River

  • Gage Height (ft) on Bronx River

  • Precipitation (in) at Central Park, Laguardia, JFK, Newark, and Staten Island

  • total 311 flooding complaints in NYC

Excluding precipitation, we calculated the monthly “iqrmax” values as:

iqrmax = 75th Quartile + 1.5 x (75th Quartile - 25th Quartile)

For precipitation, we will simply consider the iqrmax as the 99th percentile of the distribution for that month and station.

We are using this iqrmax figure as an outlier threshold.

When an daily data point exceeds its iqrmax for the month it falls within, we will consider that datapoint to indicate the possibility of a significant storm.

We will create a storm index from 1-5. The storm index will have a maximum possible value 5, meaning all 5 data sources have statistically significant “outlier” values for the day. Otherwise, the storm index will range from 0-5 based on how many of our data sources have an outlier for the given day.

%%sql
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS storm_events AS
with storm_dates_all AS
(
    SELECT DISTINCT date::date as date FROM  tidal_battery_highs_events
    WHERE waterlevel_stnd_ft_gtmax = 1
    UNION
    SELECT DISTINCT date::date as date FROM usgs_bronx_gage_daily_high_events
    WHERE discharge_cfs_gtmax = 1
    OR gage_height_ft_max_gtmax = 1
    UNION
    SELECT DISTINCT date::date as date FROM ncei_precip_daily_events
    WHERE prcp_gt99 = 1
    UNION
    SELECT DISTINCT date::date as date FROM nyc_311_flooding_events
    WHERE num_complaints_gtmax = 1
),
storm_atts AS (
    SELECT 
        dsd.date, 
        CASE WHEN usgs.discharge_cfs_gtmax IS NULL THEN 0 ELSE usgs.discharge_cfs_gtmax END AS discharge_cfs_gtmax,
        CASE WHEN usgs.gage_height_ft_max_gtmax IS NULL THEN 0 ELSE usgs.gage_height_ft_max_gtmax END AS gage_height_ft_max_gtmax,
        CASE WHEN td.waterlevel_stnd_ft_gtmax IS NULL THEN 0 ELSE td.waterlevel_stnd_ft_gtmax END AS waterlevel_stnd_ft_gtmax,
        CASE WHEN ncei.prcp_gt99 IS NULL THEN 0 ELSE ncei.prcp_gt99 END AS prcp_gt99,
        CASE WHEN nyc311.num_complaints_gtmax IS NULL THEN 0 ELSE nyc311.num_complaints_gtmax END AS num_complaints_gtmax
    FROM 
    storm_dates_all dsd 
    LEFT JOIN usgs_bronx_gage_daily_high_events usgs ON dsd.date = usgs.date
    LEFT JOIN tidal_battery_highs_events td ON dsd.date = td.date
    LEFT JOIN ncei_precip_daily_events ncei ON dsd.date = ncei.date
    LEFT JOIN nyc_311_flooding_events nyc311 ON dsd.date = nyc311.date
),
possible as (
SELECT DISTINCT
date,
discharge_cfs_gtmax,
gage_height_ft_max_gtmax,
waterlevel_stnd_ft_gtmax,
prcp_gt99,
num_complaints_gtmax,
discharge_cfs_gtmax + gage_height_ft_max_gtmax + waterlevel_stnd_ft_gtmax + prcp_gt99 + num_complaints_gtmax AS storm_index
FROM storm_atts
ORDER BY storm_index ASC, date DESC
)
SELECT * FROM possible WHERE storm_index > 0;

 * postgresql+psycopg2://docker:***@0.0.0.0:25432/storms
Done.

%%sql 
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS storm_days AS
SELECT 
    st.date, 
    st.storm_index,
    nyc311.num_complaints,
    st.discharge_cfs_gtmax, 
    usgs.discharge_cfs,
    st.gage_height_ft_max_gtmax, 
    usgs.gage_height_ft_max,
    st.waterlevel_stnd_ft_gtmax, 
    td.waterlevel_stnd_ft,
    st.prcp_gt99, 
    si.prcp as staten_island_prcp,
    lag.prcp as laguardia_prcp,
    nwk.prcp as newark_prcp,
    cp.prcp as central_park_prcp,
    jfk.prcp as jfk_prcp,
    st.num_complaints_gtmax
FROM storm_events st 
LEFT JOIN usgs_bronx_gage_daily usgs ON st.date = usgs.date
LEFT JOIN tidal_battery_highs_daily_max td ON st.date = td.date
LEFT JOIN ncei_precip_daily_si si ON st.date = si.date
LEFT JOIN ncei_precip_daily_lag lag ON st.date = lag.date
LEFT JOIN ncei_precip_daily_nwk nwk ON st.date = nwk.date
LEFT JOIN ncei_precip_daily_cp cp ON st.date = cp.date
LEFT JOIN ncei_precip_daily_jfk jfk ON st.date = jfk.date
LEFT JOIN nyc_311_flooding_events nyc311 ON st.date = nyc311.date
WHERE num_complaints IS NOT NULL
ORDER BY date, num_complaints DESC;

SELECT * FROM storm_days LIMIT 5;

The columns suffixed by “_gtmax” indicate whether the data value exceeds its outlier threshold.

As you can see above, the most severe weather events can span consecutive days. Lets group these multi day storms into a single record each. We can find groups having consecutive days using the dense_rank window function to count peer groups.

%%sql
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS storm_durations AS
SELECT 
row_number() over () as storm_id,
min("date") as start_date, 
max("date") as end_date, 
max(storm_index) as storm_index_max,
sum(num_complaints) as num_complaints,
max(num_complaints_gtmax) as num_complaints_gtmax,
max(discharge_cfs) as discharge_cfs_max,
max(discharge_cfs_gtmax) as discharge_cfs_gtmax,
max(gage_height_ft_max) as gage_height_ft_max,
max(gage_height_ft_max_gtmax) as gage_height_ft_max_gtmax,
max(waterlevel_stnd_ft) as waterlevel_stnd_ft_max,
max(waterlevel_stnd_ft_gtmax) as waterlevel_stnd_ft_gtmax,
max(prcp_gt99) as prcp_99,
sum(staten_island_prcp) as staten_island_prcp_total,
sum(laguardia_prcp) as laguardia_prcp_total,
sum(newark_prcp) as newark_prcp_total,
sum(central_park_prcp) as central_park_prcp_total,
sum(jfk_prcp) as jfk_prcp_total
FROM (
    SELECT "date", 
    storm_index, 
    num_complaints,
    num_complaints_gtmax,
    discharge_cfs,
    discharge_cfs_gtmax,
    gage_height_ft_max,
    gage_height_ft_max_gtmax,
    waterlevel_stnd_ft,
    waterlevel_stnd_ft_gtmax,
    prcp_gt99,
    staten_island_prcp,
    laguardia_prcp,
    newark_prcp,
    central_park_prcp,
    jfk_prcp,
    date - (dense_rank() over (order by date))::int g 
    FROM storm_days
    ) s
GROUP BY s.g
ORDER BY 1;

SELECT * FROM storm_durations ORDER BY num_complaints DESC LIMIT 5;

311 Complaint Aggregation#

Using the neighborhood tabulation areas, we can aggregate the flooding 311 complaints for spatial analysis.

All-time flooding complaints by NTA#

Which NTAs are most prone to flooding complaints?

%%sql 
CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW nta_most_flood_complaints AS
SELECT COUNT(nyc311.*) as num_complaints, nta.ntacode as ntacode, nta.geom as geom, nta.ntaname as ntaname
FROM nyc_311_flooding nyc311
JOIN nyc_nta_2010 nta ON ST_Contains(nta.geom, nyc311.geom)
GROUP BY nta.ntacode, nta.ntaname, nta.geom
ORDER BY num_complaints DESC;

SELECT ntaname, num_complaints
FROM nta_most_flood_complaints
LIMIT 10;

Complaints by NTA-storm#

For each storm, how many complaints did each NTA have?

For each storm, what percentage of total complaints did each NTA have?

%%sql
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS storm_nta_complaints AS
WITH storms as(
   SELECT sd.storm_id, nyc311.*
   FROM nyc_311_flooding nyc311
   RIGHT JOIN storm_durations sd 
   ON nyc311.date BETWEEN sd.start_date AND sd.end_date
),
storm_nta_total AS (
    SELECT storm_id, nta.ntacode, nta.ntaname, nta.geom, COUNT(unique_key) as storm_nta_total_complaints
    FROM storms LEFT JOIN nyc_nta_2010 nta ON ST_Intersects(storms.geom, nta.geom)
    GROUP BY storm_id, nta.ntacode, nta.ntaname, nta.geom
),
storm_total AS(
    SELECT storm_id, SUM(storm_nta_total_complaints) as storm_total_complaints
    FROM storm_nta_total
    GROUP BY storm_id
)

SELECT snt.storm_id, 
snt.ntacode, 
snt.ntaname, 
snt.storm_nta_total_complaints,
snt.storm_nta_total_complaints / st.storm_total_complaints as storm_complaints_percent, 
geom 
FROM storm_nta_total snt JOIN storm_total st ON snt.storm_id = st.storm_id;

SELECT storm_id, ntacode, ntaname, storm_nta_total_complaints, storm_complaints_percent 
FROM storm_nta_complaints ORDER BY storm_complaints_percent DESC LIMIT 10;

Flooding Complaint Clustering#

We can use complaint proximity as a proxy for spatial flooding susceptibility. The code below uses the ST_ClusterDBSCAN window function to identify clusters of 311 flooding complaints within 1 kilometer (~3281 ft) of one another having a minimum of 20 complaints for each storm. For each of these complaint clusters, the concave hull of the cluster points is used to represent the area impacted by the flooding event.

%%sql
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS storm_complaint_clusters AS
with storms as(
   SELECT sd.storm_id, nyc311.*
   FROM nyc_311_flooding nyc311
   RIGHT JOIN storm_durations sd 
   ON nyc311.date BETWEEN sd.start_date AND sd.end_date
),
clusters AS(
    SELECT 
    storm_id,
    unique_key,
    ST_ClusterDBSCAN(geom_2263, eps := 3281, minpoints := 20) OVER(PARTITION BY storm_id) as clst_id,
    geom
    FROM storms 
)
SELECT 
row_number() over () as id,
storm_id,
clst_id, 
count(clusters.*) as num_complaints, 
ST_ConcaveHull(ST_Collect(geom), 0.3) as geom
FROM clusters
WHERE clst_id IS NOT NULL
GROUP BY storm_id, clst_id;

 * postgresql+psycopg2://docker:***@0.0.0.0:25432/storms
Done.

[]

What identified clusters had the most complaints?

%%sql
SELECT scc.storm_id, st.start_date, st.end_date, scc.clst_id, scc.num_complaints 
FROM storm_complaint_clusters scc JOIN storm_durations st on scc.storm_id = st.storm_id
ORDER BY num_complaints DESC 
LIMIT 10;

Flooding Susceptibility#

As a proxy for flood susceptibility over the entire analysis period, we can use the intersection of all clusters identified for all storms.

%%sql
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS storm_complaint_clusters_intersection AS
SELECT ST_Union(ST_Intersection(a.geom, b.geom)) as geom
FROM storm_complaint_clusters a, storm_complaint_clusters b
WHERE a.id < b.id
AND ST_Intersects(a.geom, b.geom);

Done.
